{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657993"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:40:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:40:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20697"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20697"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.32,0,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13573"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105829"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13573"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88298"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"11657"},{"type":"tags","id":"11719"},{"type":"tags","id":"12574"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32591"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105829"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman presents with significant weight loss, amenorrhea, and excessive exercise. Her body mass index is 16 kg/m\u00b2, with dry skin, lanugo hair, and bradycardia. Laboratory tests show potassium 2.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.0) and haemoglobin 110 g/L (120-150).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pathological findings is most characteristic of this patient\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gelatinous transformation of bone marrow","Decreased fat in bone marrow","Increased bone mineral density","Hyperplasia of thyroid follicular cells","Proliferation of pancreatic beta cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of anorexia nervosa, including significant weight loss, amenorrhea, bradycardia, and physical findings consistent with starvation and hormonal changes. The most characteristic pathological finding in anorexia nervosa is \u003Cstrong\u003Egelatinous transformation of bone marrow\u003C/strong\u003E. This involves a paradoxical increase in fat within the bone marrow associated with deposition of mucinous matrix material. This finding is considered virtually pathognomonic for anorexia nervosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased fat in bone marrow\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because anorexia nervosa paradoxically shows increased (not decreased) fat in the bone marrow, despite overall fat loss elsewhere in the body.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased bone mineral density\u003C/strong\u003E - Anorexia nervosa is actually associated with decreased bone density due to low estrogen levels, similar to postmenopausal osteoporosis. The low estrogen state results from suppression of the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperplasia of thyroid follicular cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Anorexia nervosa is associated with decreased thyroid hormone release and symptoms of hypothyroidism (cold intolerance, bradycardia, constipation), but not with hyperplasia of thyroid follicular cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProliferation of pancreatic beta cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a feature of anorexia nervosa. The endocrine abnormalities in anorexia primarily affect the hypothalamic-pituitary axis and thyroid function rather than pancreatic islet cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther pathological findings in anorexia nervosa include electrolyte abnormalities (particularly hypokalaemia, which can lead to cardiac arrhythmias and sudden death), anemia, lymphopenia, and hypoalbuminemia. The cardiac complications, particularly arrhythmias due to electrolyte disturbances, represent the most common cause of death in these patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anorexia nervosa is characterized by self-induced starvation with marked weight loss, while bulimia involves binge eating followed by purging behaviors.","Anorexia nervosa has the highest mortality rate of any psychiatric disorder, with cardiac arrhythmias from electrolyte disturbances being a major cause of death.","Endocrine abnormalities in anorexia nervosa include amenorrhea due to decreased gonadotropin-releasing hormone secretion and reduced thyroid hormone release.","Gelatinous transformation of bone marrow (increased fat with mucinous matrix deposition) is virtually pathognomonic for anorexia nervosa."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 9; page 435-436."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88298"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20697"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88298"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T09:56:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T09:56:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13573"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105829"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","l